description:
'''Art rock''' is [[rock music]] that aims to distinguish the genre from [[popular entertainment]],{{sfn|Campbell|2012|p=393}} with the term typically being applied as the middle ground between [[Corporate rock|mainstream]] and [[experimental rock]]. Art rock primarily draws influences from the wider [[art world]]  and [[Academic art|academia]]; which includes [[contemporary art]], [[art music]], [[Avant-garde|avant-garde art]], [[experimental music]], [[avant-garde music]], alongside [[classical music]] and [[jazz]]. The term is sometimes deployed interchangeably with "[[progressive rock]]" and to refer to some experimental rock acts.

Critics have defined art rock as a "rejection" of rock music intended solely for the purpose of popular entertainment or [[Dance music|dancing]].{{sfn|Campbell|2012|p=393}} The term was closely associated with a specific period beginning over 1966 and 1967.{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=49}} Its usage waned after the late-1970s{{sfn|Campbell|2012|p=251}} while elements of the style were infused into various popular music genres through the 1990s.

